<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1911-03-02T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1911-03-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="20" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d20">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 125.2173/8.</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Minister</gloss> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Brussells</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1911-03-02"><hi rend="italic">March 2,
                                1911</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 115.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to report that complying
                            with the Department’s instruction No. 80 of December 3 last,<note n="1" xml:id="d20fn1">Not printed.</note> I duly applied to the foreign
                            office for the recognition of Mr. Charles C. Broy as American vice and
                            deputy consul general at Boma, Congo. In reply I received notice of the
                            formal recognition of Mr. Broy in the capacity named. I herewith
                            transmit a copy of a note<note n="1" xml:id="d20fn2">Not printed.</note>
                            from the minister for foreign affairs which accompanied the
                            authorization.</p>
                        <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Charles Page
                            Bryan.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>